## Conclusion

Littering is a multifaceted environmental problem with significant ecological, economic, and health consequences. It contaminates soil, water, and air; harms wildlife; disrupts critical ecosystem processes; and contributes to climate change. The economic costs of managing litter and its indirect impacts on ecosystem services and public health are substantial. Addressing littering requires a comprehensive approach that includes behavioral change, effective policy enforcement, public education, and investment in waste management infrastructure.

Given the evidence, it is imperative that governments, communities, and individuals collaborate to reduce littering through stricter regulations, enhanced recycling programs, and public awareness campaigns. Failure to act will exacerbate environmental degradation, threaten biodiversity, and impose increasing economic and health burdens globally.

